- Time-series data from 2019â€“2021  


ðŸ“ˆ Sample Visualizations

- Line plots showing how unemployment changed in each state
- Bar charts ranking states by average unemployment
- Heatmaps to spot high-unemployment periods by region
- Correlation heatmap of employment-related factors
- Interactive scatter plot using Plotly


 ðŸ’¡ Key Takeaways

- Some states and regions were consistently hit harder by unemployment
- The year 2020 saw a sharp spike in unemployment across the country
- There's a clear negative correlation between the number of employed people and the unemployment rate
- Labour force participation also impacts unemployment in many regions.

  Conclusion
  
  The analysis revealed how unemployment rates significantly fluctuated during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, and highlighted which states and regions were most affected.
  Interactive and comparative visualizations helped uncover correlations between employment, labour participation, and unemployment rates.



